	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				HOW TO MAKE YOUR ENCHANTER SMILE <BR>
<BR>
This is a guide for how to best manage high level mezzable pulls (lvl 45 pulls and up, like old seb, karnors, guk, many other places, etc) and what each member of your group should do. Here are the main characters:<BR>
<BR>
Puller: Ok the pullers job is to pull the mobs. First, he must let the party know how many mobs are being pulled. This should be done with a macro that he clicks once for each mob pulled. If puller gets a very bad pull of 5 plus (3 plus if reds) or more he should not train back to party. He should stop in clear spot and die (yes this sucks but you just saved everyone else and earned some respect, you will now be in demand for all groups, believe me word spreads fast). Now the tricky part. Second, he should stop a bit before the party to wait for the enchanter to mez the first mob, once mezzed if only one more mob he pulls to party to separate mobs and then he waits for main assist to start attacking. Now if it was a 3 pull he should pull mobs then stop wait for first mob to be mezzed, pull remaining two mobs half distance to party and again wait for second mob to be mezzed then once its mezzed pull third mob to party and wait for main assist to attack. Why the three stops, it creates separation of the mobs for targeting, making it much easier to remez, slow and debuff all mobs. He is going to get a bit beat up and does not attack until targets mezzed and main assist has attacked. During all this it helps to be taunting the mobs. The reason these two task (pulling and main assist) are separated is that it&#8217;s much easier for the main assist to set target when he is not being beaten on and moving to the party like the puller is. Plus a lot of groups use a monk to FD split the pulls and he will be FD and argoed and the main assist is open to attack or tag.<BR>
<BR>
Main Assist: He waits with party for puller and chanter to get extra mobs mezzed then once puller is at group with one mob he attacks. He should not rush the mob as this can mess up the targeting of the chanter and shaman, wait till it&#8217;s brought to you. Once there is only one mob not mezzed, hit your hot key to announce the target. After this hot key all other can now use there (slash)/assist main puller. Now once you are on a mob stay on it till its dead (99% of the time) or switch only when the chanter says switch (1% of the time, hopefully rare thing to happen but can happen if add shows up that is unmezzable or deep red, in this case the chanter will take care of current mob and you switch). If your ever not sure which mob, wait and taunt while mobs get under control. When first mob is dead make sure chanter has given the ok to break. Also always leave any mob caster that is mezzed till the end (chanter will use it for mana with ToT). Always break the warrior mobs first. If tagging and it&#8217;s a multiple pull you should now follow puller pattern above of stop and mez, move, stop and mez again if needed till only one mob is now NOT mezzed, then he starts attacking.<BR>
<BR>
Shaman/second chanter slowing: Mobs should be slowed right away, this does two things, its buys time for the party (they take less damage) and makes it a lot easier for the chanter to get off a mez with a slowed mob on him. Yes you might argo a mob sometimes but it means they are not on the chanter or cleric so party still ok. Again do not attack something on you; it&#8217;s the chanters job to get it off you. Once all mobs are slowed back out of the way.<BR>
<BR>
Primary Healer: Watches health of puller, heals if he is taking too much. Once mezzing starts his priorities are; first keep the enchanter alive (if he takes any damage heal, do not wait, a caster will not last long with 2 or 3 mobs on him, overheal if you have to just keep him alive), second is keep the main assist alive, third is the rest of the party. (at lower levels the prim healer could stun/root to help the chanter but once lvl 40 plus should only worry about heals)<BR>
<BR>
Secondary Healer: Your main job is to heal the cleric if he takes any damage. Period. Don&#8217;t wait for him to be down any, if he even takes a sliver of damage heal him to full. Second is help with the healing of chanter (quick heals always). Third heal the party. Now it&#8217;s recommended that the secondary healer use mainly quick casting heals (always on chanters as cleric will cast the big heals on him) this makes it easier for him to keep someone alive till the cleric&#8217;s slow casting bigger heal goes off.<BR>
<BR>
Enchanter: Ok he is targeting first target he can, he then cast mez as soon as he can. Now if all goes right then if follows these events. <BR>
<BR>
On a 2-mob pull: pull, mez, pull to party, attack 2nd mob by main assist On a 3-mob pull: pull, mez, pull half distance to party, mez, pull to party, attack 3rd mob by main assist<BR>
<BR>
Now the bad pulls:<BR>
<BR>
On 2-mob bad pull: Pull, mez resisted, hope to get one mezzed, group taunts, stuns, roots both mobs (no attacks), mez one, now main assist attacks unmezzed target<BR>
<BR>
On 3-mob bad pull: Pull, mez resisted, hope to get one mezzed, group taunts, stuns, roots both mobs (no attacks), if one not mezzed then chanter will chain stun to buy time for another attempt at mezzing one. At this time usually one on cleric (argo from healing chanter) one on shaman (argo from slows) and one on chanter. Main assist should make the call to attack one on cleric, chanter will continue to stun and attempt to mez the one on him. If he fails then chanter should yell out evac or zone as too much mana has been spent trying to get control. Also evac/zone should happen when 2 or 3 mobs attacking and chanter or cleric goes down.<BR>
<BR>
Rest of Party: Rule number one; stay back and out of the way. There will be plenty of time to see the mobs, remember that enchanter/slower have to click on the mob to target and they will be quite pissed if you are in there way. If bad pull or resisted mez then you can assist the chanter by rooting the mob, taunting it, snaring it, stunning it (really anything to help but DO NOT DO ANY DAMAGE) or become a third healer. Tanks only attack when main assist is fighting, casters wait for mob to be 25 percent down in health then send in the pets, dot and nuke away. <BR>
<BR>
Notes:<BR>
<BR>
Party only has one Tank: He is now the puller and main assist and still needs to follow the above procedures for both. Not much different but all healers should add him to the must keep alive list<BR>
<BR>
Pets: Can be an enchanter&#8217;s worse nightmare. Mage and Necro Pets 99% of the time are fine. Why, because mage/necro&#8217;s do not engage the main target until its down a quarter of health. So on initial pull very little chance of them getting mob argo on them and pet defending there master. Enchanter and SK pets, NEVER in multi pull mez environments (I should not have to tell you). Shaman should only have a pet if group only has one tank and no other pets, all other times no pet. The reason being is shaman always slows on pull, they will be getting argoed by mobs and wolf can&#8217;t help not attacking mob on master. Now shaman has to waste time pulling wolf off when he could be slowing other mobs or healing if needed. In these cases they are just not worth the damage they cause.<BR>
<BR>
Adds: If during the fight an additional mob joins the fight, anyone who see it should hit there hot key Add so everyone knows there is another to mez. Once mezzed then its back to normal. If add is unmezzable then enchanter has two choices charm if possible or if deep red then yell to party to switch targets. Main assist switches to new target and chanter handles old mob.<BR>
<BR>
When the plan is executed right it is truly awesome! You have just made your Enchanters Day  
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
